# Python Class Documentation Rule

Use Google-style class docstrings for public classes, dataclasses, Pydantic models, service classes, lifecycle managers, API schemas, and architecture-boundary classes.

A class docstring should explain what the class represents, what responsibility it owns, and any important invariants, side effects, or architecture boundaries.

Document constructor arguments in the class docstring when they are part of the public contract or not obvious from type hints.

Document public attributes with an Attributes section for dataclasses, DTOs, Pydantic models, and classes whose attributes are intended to be read by other modules.

Do not document every private implementation detail. Avoid docstrings that merely repeat class or field names.

For Pydantic models, prefer Field descriptions for request/response schema fields.